In C++, there is no native support for streaming a 128-bit integer directly using `iostream`. However, you can print a `__int128` variable by converting it to a string representation first and then printing that string. Below I'll provide examples for both signed `__int128` and unsigned `__uint128_t`.

For signed `__int128`:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>

std::string int128ToString(__int128 num) {
    std::string str;
    if (num == 0) return "0";

    bool negative = false;
    if (num < 0) {
        negative = true;
        num = -num;
    }

    while (num > 0) {
        int digit = num % 10;
        str = char('0' + digit) + str;
        num /= 10;
    }

    if (negative) {
        str = "-" + str;
    }

    return str;
}

int main() {
    __int128 num = static_cast<__int128>(-1234567890123456789LL) * -9876543210987654321LL;
    std::cout << int128ToString(num) << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```

For unsigned `__uint128_t`:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>

std::string uint128ToString(__uint128_t num) {
    std::string str;
    if (num == 0) return "0";

    while (num > 0) {
        int digit = num % 10;
        str = char('0' + digit) + str;
        num /= 10;
    }

    return str;
}

int main() {
    __uint128_t num = static_cast<__uint128_t>(1234567890123456789ULL) * 9876543210987654321ULL;
    std::cout << uint128ToString(num) << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```

Note that these functions convert the `__int128` to a string in reverse order by taking the remainder when dividing by 10, which corresponds to the least significant digit, and then dividing the `__int128` by 10 in a loop until the number becomes 0. The resulting string gets its characters prepended (effectively reversing the order of digits) to build the number's string representation.

Keep in mind that not all platforms and compilers support `__int128`. It is typically available on 64-bit platforms with GCC or Clang compilers. If you are using a different platform or compiler, you may need to use a library or custom implementation to handle 128-bit integers.

In C, there is no built-in type named `__int128`, but GCC and Clang provide this as an extension for 128-bit integers. Similar to C++, there is no standard way to directly print a `__int128` using the `printf` family of functions because the standard `%` format specifiers do not have a specifier for 128-bit integers. Instead, you need to convert the `__int128` to a string and print the string.

Here is a simple example of how to do this in C for both signed `__int128` and unsigned `__uint128_t` using GCC or Clang extensions:

```c
#include <stdio.h>

void print_int128(__int128 n) {
    if(n == 0) {
        printf("0");
        return;
    }

    if(n < 0) {
        putchar('-');
        n = -n;
    }

    char str[40] = {0}; // 128-bit int can be up to 39 characters plus a null terminator
    char* strp = &str[sizeof(str)-1]; // Start at the end of the buffer

    while(n != 0) {
        *(--strp) = '0' + (n % 10);
        n /= 10;
    }

    printf("%s", strp);
}

void print_uint128(__uint128_t n) {
    if(n == 0) {
        printf("0");
        return;
    }

    char str[40] = {0};
    char* strp = &str[sizeof(str)-1];

    while(n != 0) {
        *(--strp) = '0' + (n % 10);
        n /= 10;
    }

    printf("%s", strp);
}

int main() {
    __int128 n = ((__int128)1234567890123456789LL) * -9876543210987654321LL;
    print_int128(n);
    printf("\n");

    __uint128_t un = ((__uint128_t)1234567890123456789ULL) * 9876543210987654321ULL;
    print_uint128(un);
    printf("\n");

    return 0;
}
```

This code defines two functions, `print_int128` for signed integers and `print_uint128` for unsigned integers. Each function converts the number to a string representation in a character array and then uses `printf` to print the resulting string.

Please remember that `__int128` and `__uint128_t` are provided as extensions by specific compilers and may not be available or work identically across all compilers. Make sure to check whether your compiler supports these extensions before using them.

C++ does not have a built-in 128-bit integer type as part of its standard types. However, some compilers such as GCC and Clang provide extensions that include `__int128` for signed 128-bit integers and `__uint128_t` for unsigned 128-bit integers. These types are not part of the C++ standard, and their availability and implementation details can vary with different compiler vendors and versions.

When using GCC or Clang on 64-bit systems, you can generally use `__int128` and `__uint128_t`. It is important to note that because these types are non-standard, you might not be able to port your code to other compilers or platforms without modifications.

Below is an example of how you might define a 128-bit integer in C++ using these compiler extensions:

```cpp
// Ensure we're using a compiler that supports __int128
#if defined(__SIZEOF_INT128__)
#include <iostream>

int main() {
    // Define a signed 128-bit integer
    __int128 myInt128 = static_cast<__int128>(1234567890123456789LL) * 9876543210987654321LL;

    // ... your code to work with myInt128

    return 0;
}
#endif
```

If you need a 128-bit integer type that works across different platforms and compilers, you could use a library like Boost.Multiprecision that provides portable 128-bit integer support along with much larger types if necessary.

For example, with Boost.Multiprecision, you can use `boost::multiprecision::int128_t` and `boost::multiprecision::uint128_t`:

```cpp
#include <boost/multiprecision/cpp_int.hpp>
#include <iostream>

int main() {
    // Define a signed 128-bit integer using Boost.Multiprecision
    boost::multiprecision::int128_t myInt128 = static_cast<boost::multiprecision::int128_t>(1234567890123456789LL) * 
                                               static_cast<boost::multiprecision::int128_t>(9876543210987654321LL);

    // Output directly using stream operators
    std::cout << myInt128 << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

Using Boost.Multiprecision allows you to work with large integer types in a standardized and compiler-agnostic manner, although with a potential performance overhead compared to native types.

`concept` is a keyword in C++ that represents a feature enabling template metaprogramming with constraints. This feature provides a way to specify requirements on template arguments, which can make template-based code clearer, more robust, and easier to understand.

Concepts allow a template author to specify constraints that serve as a contract: a type must meet these constraints to be used as a template argument for a given template. If a type does not satisfy a concept, the program is ill-formed, and a compiler error will be produced.

In earlier stages of development, before being standardized in C++20, concepts were experimented with as a Technical Specification (TS), known as "Concepts TS". Hence, the "fconcept-ts" you mentioned appears to be a reference to this experimental phase. However, the "f" in "fconcept-ts" might be a typo or a misinterpretation, and it should be just "Concepts TS".

The Concepts Technical Specification allowed for field-testing concepts before they became a part of the official C++ standard. The Concepts TS was published as ISO/IEC TS 19217:2015.

Starting with C++20, concepts became an official part of the C++ language. They are used in conjunction with template definitions and can be defined with the `concept` keyword followed by a concept name and a constraint expression.

Here is a simple example of a concept in C++20:

```cpp
#include <concepts>
#include <iostream>

// A concept that checks if a type supports the addition operator
template<typename T>
concept Addable = requires(T a, T b) {
    { a + b } -> std::convertible_to<T>;
};

// A function that uses the Addable concept
template<Addable T>
T add(T a, T b) {
    return a + b;
}

int main() {
    std::cout << add(3, 4) << std::endl;      // OK: int supports addition
    // std::cout << add("a", "b") << std::endl; // Error: const char* does not satisfy Addable
    return 0;
}
```

This allows you to write more expressive and type-safe generic code. If you attempt to instantiate a template with a type that does not meet the requirements of the specified concept, you will get a compiler error that is typically more informative than errors arising from traditional SFINAE (Substitution Failure Is Not An Error) techniques.

Remember that to use concepts in C++, you need to have a compiler that supports the C++20 standard or later.

To remove the warning, explicitly specify the concept as the type qualification for your variable instead of using `auto`. Here's a brief example:

```cpp
// Assuming `Addable` is a concept you've defined
template<Addable T>
void func(T param) {
    Addable auto var = param; // C++20 syntax for constrained auto
    // ... do something with var
}
```
The `Addable auto` syntax is new with C++20 and applies the `Addable` constraint to the `var` variable, eliminating the warning that `auto` would otherwise generate due to the loss of the concept constraint. If your compiler does not support C++20's constrained auto, you would need to specify the concept as a template parameter:

```cpp
template<Addable T>
void func(T param) {
    T var = param; // Using T directly
    // ... do something with var
}
```

This ensures that `var` is constrained by the `Addable` concept, removing any warnings related to concept constraints.

Make sure your compiler supports C++20 and the syntax you are using to implement this solution.

In C++, to include multiple types in a concept, you define the constraints that make them "adorable," and then any type that meets these constraints is considered to adhere to the concept. Here’s an example of how you could create a concept named `Adorable`:

```cpp
#include <concepts>
#include <string>

// Define a concept named Adorable
template<typename T>
concept Adorable = requires(T x) {
    // Here you define constraints that make a type "Adorable"
    { x.isCute() } -> std::same_as<bool>; // The type must have a member function isCute that returns a bool
    { x.isFriendly() } -> std::convertible_to<bool>; // The type must have a member function isFriendly that can be converted to a bool
    // You can add more constraints as necessary
};

// An example type that satisfies the Adorable concept
class Puppy {
public:
    bool isCute() const {
        return true; // Simplified for example purposes
    }
    bool isFriendly() const {
        return true; // Simplified for example purposes
    }
};

// A function template that uses the Adorable concept
template<Adorable T>
void cuddle(const T& pet) {
    if (pet.isCute() && pet.isFriendly()) {
        // ... enjoy time with the pet
    }
}

int main() {
    Puppy myPuppy;
    cuddle(myPuppy); // This would work because Puppy satisfies the Adorable concept

    // Try to call cuddle with a type that does not satisfy the Adorable concept
    // std::string rock;
    // cuddle(rock); // Error: std::string does not satisfy the Adorable concept

    return 0;
}
```

In this example, we've defined an `Adorable` concept that requires types to have two member functions, `isCute` and `isFriendly`, both of which should be boolean in nature (either returning `bool` or convertible to `bool`). The `Puppy` class satisfies these requirements, so we can use it with any function that constrains its template parameters with the `Adorable` concept.

If a type does not meet the specified constraints of the concept, attempting to use it as an argument for a function template constrained by the `Adorable` concept will result in a compile-time error. This error helps programmers catch mistakes early in the development process.

To include more types as "adorable," simply define them with the required members or behaviors specified by the concept, and make sure they can be used with functions or templates that are constrained by the Adorable concept. The concept mechanism in C++ allows you to expressively define and use such constraints across various types.

Yes, in some programming environments, you can use a structured exception handling mechanism like try-catch blocks to handle memory access violations. However, this is not standard C++ behavior, and it relies on platform-specific extensions or OS-specific behavior.

For example, on Windows, you can use Structured Exception Handling (SEH) to catch access violations:

```cpp
#include <windows.h>
#include <iostream>

int main() {
    int* pBadPtr = nullptr; // A bad pointer
    __try {
        // This will cause an access violation
        *pBadPtr = 42;
    }
    __except (EXCEPTION_EXECUTE_HANDLER) {
        std::cout << "Access violation caught!" << std::endl;
    }
    return 0;
}
```

On UNIX-like systems (including Linux and macOS), C++ does not have built-in support for catching such hardware exceptions using try-catch blocks. However, the OS might deliver a signal like `SIGSEGV` (segmentation fault) to the process, which you can handle using the `signal` function from `<csignal>`. Doing this in a signal handler can be unsafe and is generally not recommended.

C++ has a standard exception handling mechanism with try-catch blocks that work with exceptions thrown by the code, using the keywords `throw`, `try`, and `catch`. However, memory access violations do not throw standard C++ exceptions, and you cannot catch them with C++'s try-catch blocks without relying on non-portable, platform-specific behavior.

It's also worth mentioning that using exceptions or signals to handle invalid memory access is not considered good practice. Such events are indicative of bugs or serious issues in the program that should be fixed. Moreover, using exceptions for regular control flow, especially to handle things like invalid memory access, can result in code that is difficult to understand and maintain.

The recommended practice is to write safe code that does not result in invalid memory accesses, using mechanisms like smart pointers and standard library containers that manage memory automatically and safely. This way, you can rely on the regular C++ exception handling to catch and respond to errors representable by standard exceptions (such as `std::bad_alloc` when memory allocation fails).

Smart pointers are a feature in C++ that provide automatic memory management through RAII (Resource Acquisition Is Initialization) which encapsulates a raw pointer and automatically deallocates the associated memory when it's no longer needed.

C++ Smart pointers are implemented as template classes in the C++ standard library header `<memory>`. There are several types of smart pointers, each intended for different use cases:

1. **`std::unique_ptr`:** This smart pointer maintains exclusive ownership of the object it points to. It cannot be copied, but it can be moved to transfer ownership to a new `std::unique_ptr`. When the `std::unique_ptr` goes out of scope, the object it owns is automatically destroyed and the memory is deallocated.

```cpp
#include <memory>

void example() {
    std::unique_ptr<int> up(new int(42)); // up owns the integer
    // No need to delete the pointer, memory is automatically freed when up goes out of scope
}
```

2. **`std::shared_ptr`:** Allows multiple `std::shared_ptr` instances to own the same object. The object is destroyed and its memory is deallocated when the last `std::shared_ptr` owning it is destroyed or reset.

```cpp
#include <memory>

void example() {
    std::shared_ptr<int> sp1(new int(42)); // sp1 owns the integer
    std::shared_ptr<int> sp2 = sp1;        // sp2 also owns the integer
    // Memory will be freed when the last shared_ptr (sp2 in this case) goes out of scope
}
```

3. **`std::weak_ptr`:** Designed to be used in conjunction with `std::shared_ptr`. It holds a non-owning reference to an object that is managed by `std::shared_ptr`. A `std::weak_ptr` does not count towards the reference count of `std::shared_ptr` it references. This helps to prevent circular references which could lead to memory leaks.

```cpp
#include <memory>

void example() {
    std::shared_ptr<int> sp(new int(42));  // sp owns the integer
    std::weak_ptr<int> wp = sp;            // wp is a weak reference to the integer
    // The integer will be deallocated when sp goes out of scope, independent of wp
}
```

Smart pointers help to prevent memory leaks and dangling pointer issues by managing the lifetime of objects and automatically freeing resources at appropriate times. They are an integral part of modern C++ programming and it is recommended to use them over raw pointers whenever possible for safer and more maintainable code.

No, in standard user-mode programming, you typically cannot manually choose the virtual address to which memory will be allocated. Memory management is handled by the operating system, and when you request memory allocation (e.g., via `malloc`, `new`, or similar functions), the operating system provides you with an available region of memory from your process’s virtual address space.

However, there are some more advanced OS-specific functions that allow you to request memory at a specific address:

**On Unix-like systems (including Linux):**

The `mmap` function can be used with `MAP_FIXED` flag to request memory at a specific address. However, using this flag is dangerous because it can silently replace existing mappings, leading to unpredictable behavior, and is highly discouraged unless you have a very good reason and you know exactly what you are doing.

```c
#include <sys/mman.h>

void *addr = ...; // the desired address
size_t length = ...; // the length of the memory to allocate

void *ptr = mmap(addr, length, PROT_READ | PROT_WRITE, MAP_PRIVATE | MAP_ANONYMOUS | MAP_FIXED, -1, 0);

if (ptr == MAP_FAILED) {
    // handle the error
}
```

**On Windows:**

The `VirtualAlloc` function can be used to allocate memory, and you can specify a preferred starting address for the block of memory using the `lpAddress` parameter. However, like with `mmap`, if you specify an address that is already in use, the function call will fail unless you also use the `MEM_TOP_DOWN` flag, which can have other side effects.

```c
#include <windows.h>

void* desiredAddress = ...; // the desired address
SIZE_T size = ...; // the size of the memory allocation

LPVOID ptr = VirtualAlloc(desiredAddress, size, MEM_COMMIT | MEM_RESERVE, PAGE_READWRITE);

if (!ptr) {
    // handle the error
}
```

Using these functions incorrectly can lead to serious program errors, including overwriting memory mappings, causing segmentation faults or general protection faults, and ultimately leading to program crashes and data corruption.

These capabilities are typically used by system-level programmers who need precise control over memory for things like implementing memory managers, working with memory-mapped hardware, or creating shared memory between processes. 

For normal application development, it is best to let the operating system handle memory allocation and not attempt to allocate memory at specific virtual addresses.

Yes, on macOS and iOS, which are both based on Darwin (a UNIX-like system), you can use `mmap` with `MAP_FIXED` to request memory at a specific address, much like on other UNIX-like systems. However, as mentioned, using `MAP_FIXED` can be dangerous and should be avoided if possible.

Here is an example of how you might use `mmap` to request memory at a specific address on macOS and iOS:

```c
#include <sys/mman.h>

void *desiredAddress = ...; // The desired start address for the memory mapping
size_t length = ...; // The length of the mapping

void *mappedAddress = mmap(desiredAddress, length, PROT_READ | PROT_WRITE, MAP_PRIVATE | MAP_ANONYMOUS | MAP_FIXED, -1, 0);

if (mappedAddress == MAP_FAILED) {
    // Handle error
}
```

Remember that specifying a desired address with `MAP_FIXED` will cause `mmap` to replace any existing mapping at that address, which can lead to unpredictable behavior if it overlaps with existing mappings that you did not mean to override.

In addition to `mmap`, on macOS, there's also the Mach interface, which provides a lower-level memory management mechanism. Functions like `vm_allocate` (to allocate memory) and `vm_map` (to map memory, with more control than `mmap`) are part of this interface.

When writing standard user-mode applications, it's usually better to rely on the operating system's memory management facilities and simply use the memory allocation functions provided by your programming language's standard library (like `new` and `delete` in C++, or `malloc` and `free` in C).

Use system-level functions like `mmap` only when you have a specific need to control memory allocation at a low level, for instance when implementing shared memory or when interacting with hardware in kernel extensions or low-level system code. Otherwise, sticking to the higher-level abstractions helps avoid hard-to-diagnose bugs and makes your code more portable and maintainable.
